"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-25-team-gb-star-says-andy-murray-unfair-advantage-paris-olympics-21298976\", \"text\": \"Andy Murrayhas an 'unfair advantage' at the 2024 Olympic tennis tournament inParis, according to fellow Team GB starKatie Boulter.  Murray dramaticallypulled out of the Olympic singleson Thursday, in what is meant to be his final event in tennis before his retirement from the sport.  The 37-year-old is nowsolely focusing on the men's doubleswithDan Evansas the British sporting icon looks to clinch the fourth Olympic medal of his career.  Boulter, who is representing Great Britain in the women's singles, withno Emma Raducanu in Paris, has explained why Murray has an 'unfair advantage'.  But it's absolutely nothing to do with tennis, it's instead to do with a quirky new hobby the British players have picked up in the French capital.  Boulter was quizzed about what it was like having Murray on the Team GB team and toldHeart Radio: 'I mean, he is probably the pro in pin collecting, he takes it very seriously.  'Ever since the accreditation line that we were picking up our badges, he was right on the ball and getting as many as he could. So, he does a slight, unfair advantage because a lot of people come up to him for selfies and he's trading that for pins, which is interesting. You know, tough to keep up!  'We all get given pins from our countries, and every other country has their own pin as well. Some have a few pins which are unique, and some are special, and some are not, but they trade them.  'So, at night you will see people go out - we went out last night, like all of us together on our Team GB bikes - looking for pins and some people that we can trade pins with.  'It's insane, it is. It's very unique and very special, but some are better than others, I will say that. I am not sure my game's there yet!'  Murraypaid an emotional farewellto Wimbledon this year and one of his sponsors, Castore, has urged those in SW19 to rename Church Road as 'Murray Mile' in his honour.  'Andy's legacy is unequalled,' Tom Beahon, Castore co-founder said. 'His desire to compete and push himself beyond his limits in order to win is inspiring.  'It only makes sense that the SW19 site where he achieved greatness should immortalise his excellence.\\u00a0As an ambassador and investor, he embodies our better never stops mentality both on and off the court and we hope the public join us in celebrating his achievements with a permanent legacy.'  ArrowMORE:Rafael Nadal faces Olympic nightmare as new injury forces him to cancel practice  ArrowMORE:Paris Olympics Opening Ceremony: Parade of Nations order explained  ArrowMORE:Israel flagbearer for Paris Olympics 'signed bombs' heading for Gaza  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"